<p align="center"><font color="#0E024D" face="Arial"><strong>PLAYER SUBMITTED STRATEGY</strong></font></p>
<div align="center"><center>

  <div align="center"><center><table border="0" width="90%">
    <tr>
      <td>
      <center><font face="Arial"><strong><b><font color="#800000">PORCUPINE!</b></font> - <small>Joss, Cazic Thule</small></strong></font><font face="Arial"></center>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td>
    <small><hr size="1" color="#C0C0C0"><P>
        I'm shocked this one hasn't already been posted, because it's such a basic Druid strategy. <P>
    You all know about Porcupines, they're covered with pokey bits and it hurts really bad to attack them.  Well, with our wonderfull line of damage shields that starts at level 9 we can do the same thing :)<P>
    You will need the following to pull this off:  Snare, Your best AC and HP buffs, (whatever)coat, Shield of (whatever), flame lick, your heal spell, and something from the stinging swarm line if you have it.  Before level 24 you want treeform memed, and after 24 just keep yourself in wolf form.<P>
    So, you locate your prey, I reccomend mid to high blues because whites can get hairy with this.  Cast all your best AC and HP buffs on yourself, and keep up your damage shield coat (it lasts almost as long as SoW so should not be a problem).  Right before you attack cast the short duration shield of (whatever) on yourself and snare the hapless bugger.  If it doesn't take, just keep trying while it beats on you (your damage shield will be doing far more than your weapon anyway, so big deal if you're not swinging).  Once it is snared hit it with Flame Lick and swarm line if you have it.  If you are above 29 you may want to hit it with Immolate instead of Flame Lick.  Melee until you are a couple bubbles of life down, then pull back and heal yourself while it catches up to you.  You may only want to wait one bubble of life if your heal spell isn't doing much yet (i.e. below level 19)  If you are below 24 and find that you can manage to get your heal spells off while being hit, then go treeform for the added mana regen (you CAN fight in treeform, you just can't move).  I found that at level 20 I could easily cast enough spells through getting hit to handle the aviak guards in lake ratheater 1 at a time. <P>
    Flame lick is important because it stops monster HP regen and lowers the critter's AC for nearly a minute (you probably will need to re-cast it). <P>
    With level 24 you get Wolf form, and the combonation of wolf form, Fire fist, and Strength of Earth transforms you from whiffmaster into someone who can actually hit.  At this point porcupining becomes easier as the damage you are doing actually begins to count for somthing, though it is still your shield that will be doing the majority of the damage.<P>
    At level 29 you get Greater Heal, which is a wonderfull boon to this fighting style, along with Immolate which lets you handle high blues with ease again.  After you put 2 DoTs onto a monster with your damage shields on you can easily outlast what's left of the poor creature.  Whites will probably hit too hard to be worthwhile with this method though.<P>
    One word to the wise, if it's a low blue you're killing, don't bother with any DoTs at all.  Your mana is better used on healing spells because it won't last for long.<P>
    I mostly stick with blues because I can often take 2 or 3 in a row, where one white will wipe me out of mana.<P>
    This method will keep your skills up and still allow you to solo.  Things will obviously go faster if you find a tank to damage shield and heal, because then you don't have to try to cast through getting hit, and a tank can hit for a decent amount of damage.<P>

Joss, Level 30 Druid on Cazic-Thule
    </small></font></p>
    <p><small><font face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></small></td>
  </tr>
